values.title: Flagship Dataset of Type 2 Diabetes from the AI-READI Project
values.description: The AI-READI (Artificial Intelligence Ready and Exploratory Atlas for Diabetes Insights) dataset consists of data collected from individuals with and without Type 2 Diabetes Mellitus (T2DM)...

values.license_and_use_terms: Public data available for download upon agreement with a license defining permitted uses. Full dataset access (including controlled-access components) contingent on entering into a Data Use Agreement. Adheres to FAIR (Findable, Accessible, Interoperable, Reusable) principles.

values.distribution_formats: Data formats vary by domain as documented in dataset documentation.

license_terms: Public data under license with defined permitted uses
Full dataset requires Data Use Agreement for controlled-access components

values.discouraged_uses: Users must adhere to license terms for public data and the Data Use Agreement for controlled-access data. Uses that would violate participant privacy protections or re-identification attempts are prohibited.

irb_approval: Approved by University of Washington Institutional Review Board (approval number STUDY00016228)
Reliance agreements with IRBs of University of Alabama at Birmingham and University of California San Diego
ethics_review_board: University of Alabama at Birmingham IRB (reliance agreement)
University of California San Diego IRB (reliance agreement)

values.is_deidentified: Public dataset is de-identified. Controlled-access dataset contains limited identifiers (5-digit zip code, demographic data) under data use agreement protections.

confidentiality_details: 5-digit zip code held under controlled access
Genetic sequencing data (future) will be held under controlled access
Past health records and medications held under controlled access
Sex, race, ethnicity held under controlled access
sensitivity_details: Sex, race, ethnicity held under controlled access

consent_type: Written informed consent provided by all participants
Informed consent document available for download during recruitment
Consent covers data collection and sharing of de-identified research data

values.note: Fields present in schema but not explicitly documented in this file beyond standard protections

values.subpopulations: Participants with and without Type 2 Diabetes Mellitus, stratified by diabetes severity. Four T2DM categories: no diabetes, pre-diabetes/lifestyle-controlled, diabetes treated with medications, insulin-controlled diabetes. Four race/ethnicity groups: Asian, Black, White, Hispanic. Equal distribution by biological sex.

values.instances: Individual participants with and without Type 2 Diabetes Mellitus (T2DM) with multi-domain measurements. Each participant represents an instance with cross-sectional data including survey responses, physical and clinical measurements, blood and urine lab results, retinal imaging, ECG, wearable device time-series (10 days), continuous blood glucose monitoring (10 days), and environmental sensor data. Target enrollment 4,000 participants across three sites, with approximately 400 participants (10%) in longitudinal follow-up.

values.note: Topics represented in instances description: Type 2 Diabetes, survey data, clinical measurements, lab results, imaging, wearable devices, environmental sensors

values.anomalies: As enrollment is ongoing (began July 18, 2023, continues through November 30, 2026), early data releases may not have achieved balanced distribution across all groups due to wave-based recruitment and ongoing enrollment.
values.sampling_strategies: Recruitment sampling procedures aimed at achieving triple-balanced distribution across four race/ethnic groups (Asian, Black, White, Hispanic), four categories of T2DM severity (no diabetes, pre-diabetes/lifestyle-controlled, diabetes treated with oral/non-insulin injectable medications, insulin-controlled diabetes), and biological sex (male, female). Recruitment in waves with monitoring and adjustment through under- and oversampling as needed.

values.version_access: Separate documentation versions align to dataset versions. Users can navigate between versions via the documentation site. FAIRhub provides version control and DOI assignment for each release.
version_details: Each dataset version has corresponding documentation version
DOI assigned to each major release

values.updates: Periodic updates to data releases are planned as enrollment proceeds (enrollment through November 30, 2026). Documentation versions align with dataset versions to ensure users can track changes across releases.
update_details: Periodic data releases as enrollment continues
Documentation versioned with dataset (e.g., v1.0.0, v2.0.0)

values.note: Update schedule covered in updates field

values.purposes: Create a flagship ethically-sourced dataset to enable future generations of artificial intelligence/machine learning (AI/ML) research to provide critical insights into type 2 diabetes mellitus (T2DM), including salutogenic pathways to return to health. Develop a foundational dataset in diabetes, agnostic to existing classification criteria, which can be used to reconstruct a temporal atlas of T2DM development and reversal towards health.

values.tasks: Enable downstream AI/ML analyses including pseudotime manifold analysis to predict disease trajectories across survey, clinical, imaging, wearable, and environmental domains related to T2DM that may not be feasible with existing data sources such as claims or electronic health records data.

values.note: No explicit grant IDs in funders field, but NIH project link available in external_resources

values.creators: AI-READI Consortium - Multi-institutional team led by Contact PI Aaron Lee (University of Washington, Department of Ophthalmology), with teams across eight institutions working on six cross-disciplinary project modules.

values.collection_mechanisms: Multi-modal data collection using hardware devices, clinical procedures, and software-driven capture. REDCap used for patient-reported questionnaires and clinical data entry.
mechanism_details: REDCap for survey data and clinical measurements entry
Retinal imaging devices exporting to DICOM format
Garmin fitness tracker for 10-day activity and heart rate monitoring
Dexcom Continuous Glucose Monitor for 10-day glucose tracking
Environmental sensors for home air quality monitoring
Laboratory equipment for blood and urine analysis
Clinical procedures (monofilament testing, cognitive function testing, visual acuity, contrast sensitivity)

values.acquisition_methods: Harmonized, multi-domain data acquisition across three collection sites (University of Washington, University of Alabama at Birmingham, University of California San Diego) using surveys, clinical exams, imaging devices, wearable sensors, and environmental monitors. In-person study visit for clinical assessments, followed by 10-day at-home monitoring with wearable devices.

values.preprocessing_strategies: Domain-specific processing and harmonization described in the Dataset Documentation for each data domain. Images exported from devices in raw format with some requiring conversion to DICOM standard format prior to upload. Data from wearable devices and sensors exported in their raw formats.
values.cleaning_strategies: Harmonization and processing across three sites with domain-specific details provided in the documentation. Quality control procedures for clinical measurements and imaging data.
values.labeling_strategies: Domain-specific labeling and annotation where applicable, as described in the documentation for each data domain. Clinical test outputs and imaging outputs labeled according to clinical standards.
